ekuleshov wrote:

&gt; --- In junit@yahoogroups.com, Jason Rogers &lt;jacaetevha@f...&gt; wrote:
&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; I see what you mean. However, one of our goals in JUnit 4 was to
&gt; &gt; &gt; remove the
&gt; &gt; &gt; recursive composition of tests. It is difficult to explain and
&gt; &gt; &gt; difficult to
&gt; &gt; &gt; support properly in test runners. What I need is an example of JUnit
&gt; &gt; &gt; 4-style
&gt; &gt; &gt; dynamic test case creation.
&gt; &gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; Nothing is coming to mind at the present time.  Let me give this some
&gt; &gt; more thought.  It may be a dead horse.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; BTW: I appreciate your openness to suggestions.
&gt;
&gt; From time to I&#39;m using something like this to verify some conditions:
&gt;
&gt; public static TestSute suite() {
&gt;   TestSuite suite = new TestSuite( &quot;Validator&quot;);
&gt;   for(...) {
&gt;     if( condition is invalid) {
&gt;       suite.addTest( new FailingTestCase( ..., new
&gt; ComparisonFailure(..., expect, actual));
&gt;     } else {
&gt;       add a regular test to the suite.
&gt;     }
&gt;   }
&gt;   return suite;
&gt; }
&gt;
We also use this approach but for a slightly different reason.  Some of 
our code connects to Salesforce.com&#39;s Enterprise Web Service (a hosted 
CRM solution).  The configuration settings for using that service are 
located in the web.xml file of our servlet.  One of the tests that run 
as a part of AllTests is to check the web.xml and make sure it&#39;s 
pointing at our mock instance of the web service so that our functional 
tests don&#39;t accidentally overwrite data that exists in production.  The 
test that runs to &quot;validate&quot; the web.xml is run initially and if it 
fails we do not build up the rest of the suite.

